messages.content: I want to create a signature for some string data. I see that Signature.create() only takes in Fields. How can I encode / convert a string value into a Field?
There’s an encoding library https://github.com/o1-labs/snarkyjs/blob/main/src/lib/encoding.ts

messages.content: Thanks for your response. What does “This function is not a valid in-snark computation” in the header comment of the function mean?

It means that you can't prove the computation that happened, meaning you can't prove to the versifier that you correctly encoded a string into a Field element. So this is something to use only outside of SmartContract methods for preprocessing
Can a string be stored as a state of a zkapp smart contract? Or do you advise against that?
You can only store Field-like datatypes in a contract accout
But you can encode the string into a Field
It looks like string encoding will yield multiple fields (field array). I read somewhere that only 8 Fields can be stored onchain. In that case, strings aren’t the best for keeping states.
thats correct, you can only store 8 field elements within a contract account
Thx. I’ll try out the encoding offchain and get back to you if I run into other issues

How about using CircuitString class? https://github.com/o1-labs/snarkyjs/blob/4c9316bdfa4a8d5ae2eb61ad25ede412ec8c0a72/src/lib/string.ts#L37
you can hash it using `hash()` and that will give you a `Field` that can be signed.

messages.content: Thanks for the idea. I already used the Encoding library mentioned above. It was enough for my use case.

The CircuitString allows you to make statements about individual characters, because each character is represented as a full field element. This comes at the cost of much worse encoding efficiency compared to the Encoding functions
